<br>
A hundred million flakes upon the land. Each one a different shade of white, each tiny star jagged and carelessly shaped by the sky.<br>
<br>
But this solitary flake, flittering down through the ceiling of the cracked and decrepit cavern was far different from the others. It bore the signs of divine purpose, as a falling star in the midnight sky. As the star descended closer to the frostbitten earth, an aura of light emanated from within. Dull and tiny at first, it intensified as it fell. The muddied shade of yellow transformed to brilliant white; the spark of light irradiated the room, bathing the packed snow and frozen dirt in celestial energy.<br>
<br>
The snowflake landed softly upon the lips of the fallen woman, and the brilliant light ceased. A weak, pulsating ember was all that remained. For reasons unknown, the kneeling man leaned his head in closer to the woman in his arms, and gently kissed upon her frozen lips.<br>
<br>
Once more a blinding flash of light permeated the room, and staring back up at him from the snowy floor with a gaze of green fire was Erollisi, the fairer of the Marr twins. Her emerald eyes looked up to him and the enormous woman spoke to him, though the words seemed far and distant to his ears. "I have answerd your prayer and I shall hold you to it...Master Pren !!...I command you to watch over this, young Maiden for in saving her life you have altered the events of her life. So I bid thee good luck Master Pren...you were a true hero today and we in the heavens are proud to know that there is still hope in man and this world..."<br>
<br>
Again Pren's sight was rent by brilliant shining light, and the goddess faded away. In her place, once again, lay the half-elf. But her bruised and broken body was whole - and then some. Her chapped and blood-caked skin now was as pale and soft as a newborn; the matted and torn hair vibrant and black as the deepest night. Her frayed rags had been replaced with a sky-blue silken robe of obvious divine origin. She began to stir back into consciousness, her eyes flashing open like the birth of a sun.<br>
<br>
Her new body quickly shook the disorientation of death, and she was on her feet in moments modestly tying the robe about her flesh. Her eyes locked on Pren's and she asked 'Who are you?', the maiden's voice carrying a hint of intrigee.<br>
<br>
Pren leaned over and retrieved his staff from the floor, bracing himself against it. Flicking a frozen tear from his cheek, slowly he spoke. "I am Baron Pren, Grandmaster of the Hearts," his tone one of quiet skepticism, "and what do they call you dear one?"<br>
<br>
Swanmay's smirk deepened, noticing her savior's uncertainty of the situation. Her melodic voice rolled from her ruby lips, "My name is Swanmay Shadowsong. Traveling bard and..." she paused, glancing over the frozen splatters of blood upon the old ice, "...occasional dragon snack."<br>
<br>
Her optimism clearly calmed Pren somewhat, and she stepped closer to him for a better look. He stood clad mostly in leathers and silks, a simple and light ensemble. Several small packs hung from his waist and shoulders. A lock of long brown hair ran down to the small of his back, and his face was covered in a scraggly beard. Lights danced in a halo around his fists, occasionally sparking off in shimmering golden rings and dying out in the cool air. One of the small rings passed through her stomach, leaving a fleeting feeling of tranquility behind, easing her next question somewhat. "Not that I am ungrateful, but how did you find me here?"<br>
<br>
"I was hunting the hounds and ursine beasts the old bitch keeps as guardians when I heard your song echoing through the ice. I thought it was just wind gusting through a new crevasse til I heard the screams. I followed the sound of your voice, and it led me here." he replied<br>
<br>
"Dragon fighter and hunter of wild beasts, and a Baron to boot. You're a full package aren't you?", she coyly stated.<br>
<br>
His left hand left the support of his staff, waved off to the side in gesture, and spoke "Oh, you know, it's noth...." Horribly losing his balance silenced his boast and he tumbled forward. Swanmay tried to catch him, but the weight brought them both crashing into a small pile of freshly fallen snow in a tangle of limbs.<br>
<br>
Pren began to laugh hard, spitting out flakes of powder and coughing intermittently while turning the earth beneath him crimson. Swanmay started to laugh, but stopped as she began to notice the wounds upon him. Slowly his laughter died down.<br>
<br>
"You're hurt!" exclaimed the petite elf.<br>
"I'm fine."<br>
"No you're not!", and she retrieved a sheet of bandages from one of his pouches.<br>
"Really, I.... ouch! Let me do it."<br>
"Don't be a baby, it's supposed to hurt."<br>
"No it isn't."<br>
"It does when I do it."<br>
"So I've noticed."<br>
<br>
The half-elf stood and harumphed, walking off behind him. He became engrossed in tending to his own wounds til a soft strumming reached his ears. Swanmay returned and sat down facing him, skillfully fingering the cords on a worse-for-wear mandolin. She tuned it as she played, adjusting it several times til the look of consternation on her face changed to satisfaction.<br>
<br>
"There we go. This will work much better."<br>
"Are you going to hit me with that then?"<br>
"No", she stated while smacking him across the knee open handed, "I wouldn't have tuned it first."<br>
<br>
Swanmay resumed her strumming and Pren felt the healing rhythms of her music, and was soon on his feet. Hobbling along with his staff for support, the two began working their way out of the frozen hell leaving a trail of gentle notes in their wake.<br>
<br>
Eventually they rounded a wide corner and a sharp gust of wind stung at their faces. Before them stretched the trackless tundra, and the world beyond.<br>
<br>
"We should rest here tonight" spoke Swanmay as she pivoted to face him, "You still need some... rest." The word died on her lips. Dropping his staff to the ground, Pren flexed his arms and clenched his fists. A gentle ripple danced from head to toe and back again, sealing and hiding all wounds as it passed over them.<br>
<br>
Pren knelt, retrieving his staff and ripping the bandages from his legs, "You've got a drum right?" Swanmay nodded in agreement. The monk smiled, "Then lets get moving. We both need a beer badly, I imagine."<br>
<br>
